# Documentation Language Policy

All documentation produced by an agent MUST be written in English by default. The only exceptions are user-facing content explicitly governed by a project rule and the conversational output with the operator.

## In scope (English MANDATORY)

The following content MUST be authored in English regardless of the project's spoken language:

### AI-facing configuration

- Rules under `mesh/rules/`, `.cursor/rules/`, `.claude/`, `.agents/` — descriptions, headers, body text, frontmatter values.
- Skills under `mesh/skills/**/`, `.cursor/skills/`, `.agents/skills/` — descriptions, instructions, workflows, templates, checklists, reference docs.
- Prompts under `mesh/prompts/`.
- Slash commands under `mesh/commands/` and their scripts under `mesh/commands/scripts/`.
- MCP server definitions under `mesh/mcp/`.
- Plan files under `.cursor/plans/` (canonical post-resolution plans).

### Technical code documentation

- `README.md`, `README.*` at any level of any project repository.
- `CHANGELOG.md`, release notes, migration guides.
- `docs/` directories inside project repos when they describe technical architecture, APIs, infrastructure, build/deploy workflows, or developer onboarding.
- Architecture Decision Records (ADRs).
- Code comments (inline and block) in source files.
- Commit messages and pull request titles/descriptions.
- Module-level docstrings, JSDoc/TSDoc, Python docstrings, Go doc comments.
- Inline configuration documentation.

## Out of scope (project rule wins)

The following content follows the project's own language rules. If a project rule requires another language (e.g. Spanish), that rule prevails over this one:

- User-facing editorial content of a project (e.g. notes inside knowledge vaults like `techcorpus`, end-user documentation aimed at non-technical readers, internal Spanish-language wikis).
- Jira / ticketing comments addressed to clients — they follow the language of the conversation thread (see project-specific Jira workflow rules).
- Operational logs explicitly defined by a project rule in another language (e.g. Tiber `bitacora-global.md` and `clientes/<id>/history.md` files which are explicitly Spanish per their own rule).
- The agent's conversational output to the operator — governed by `global.mdc`.

## Conflict resolution

When a project rule and this rule disagree:

1. The project rule prevails ("project wins").
2. The agent must still keep technical glossary in English even inside a non-English document: command names, proper nouns, acronyms, identifiers (cloud project IDs, service names, env var names), configuration keys, library/tool names.
3. If the project rule is ambiguous about a specific artifact (e.g. it mandates Spanish for "notes" but a new `README.md` is being added), default to English under this rule.

## Rationale

- AI-facing files are consumed by assistants tuned primarily on English content; English maximizes compatibility and reduces translation drift.
- Technical code documentation lives next to source code that is itself written in English (identifiers, APIs, libraries) and is consumed by engineers across teams; mixing languages fragments searchability and onboarding.
- User-facing content is excluded because its audience and authoring conventions are defined by the project itself.
